tics Circle Award for Best Director of a Canadian Film|Best Director of a Canadian Film]]\n|Xavier Dolan\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor in a Canadian Film|Best Actor in a Canadian Film]]\n|Antoine Olivier Pilon\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actress in a Canadian Film|Best Actress in a Canadian Film]]\n|Anne Dorval\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Canadian Film|Best Supporting Actress in a Canadian Film]]\n|Suzanne Cl\u00e9ment\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Best Screenplay for a Canadian Film\n|Xavier Dolan\n|{{won}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |[[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards]]\n| rowspan=1| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards 2014|8 December 2014]]\n| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n!\n|{{nom}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=1|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wafca.com/awards/2014.htm|title=The 2014 WAFCA Awards|publisher=[[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association]]|date=|accessdate=11 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209014231/http://www.wafca.com/awards/2014.htm|archive-date=9 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 87th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Canadian submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3612616|Mommy}}\n* {{mojo title|mommy|Mommy}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|mommy_2015|Mommy}}\n* {{metacritic film|mommy|Mommy}}\n\n{{Xavier Dolan}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for ''Mommy''\n|list =\n{{ACCT Best Picture}}\n{{Cannes Film Festival Jury Prize}}\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Foreign Film}}\n{{Prix Iris for Best Film}}\n}}\n{{Canadian submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mommy}}\n[[Category:2014 drama films]]\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Film C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Picture Genie and Canadian Screen Award winners]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Films about parenting]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Xavier Dolan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Montreal]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2014 film}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mommy\n| image          = Mommy-by-xavier-dolan-cannes-poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Xavier Dolan]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Xavier Dolan\n* [[Nancy Grant]]}}\n| writer         = Xavier Dolan\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Anne Dorval]]\n* [[Antoine Olivier Pilon]]\n* [[Suzanne Cl\u00e9ment]]}}\n| music          = Noia\n| cinematography = [[Andr\u00e9 Turpin]]\n| editing        = Xavier Dolan\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Metafilms\n* [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de d\u00e9veloppement des entreprises culturelles]]\n* Sons of Manual\n* [[Super \u00c9cran]]\n* [[T\u00e9l\u00e9film Canada]]}}\n| distributor    = [[Les Films S\u00e9ville]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2014|05|22|[[2014 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2014|09|19|Canada}}\n| runtime        = 138 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 138:12--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/mommy-film | title=''Mommy'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=29 January 2015 | accessdate=29 January 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419085614/http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/mommy-film | archive-date=19 April 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = French\n| budget         = $4.9 million<ref>{{cite web|title=Mommy et les autres : combien co\u00fbte un prix \u00e0 Cannes?|date=26 May 2014|author=Daudens, Florent|author2=Niosi, Laurence|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/arts_et_spectacles/2014/05/26/006-palmares-cannes-couts-budget-films-mommy-xavier-dolan.shtml|work=Ici.radio-canada.ca|access-date=20 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219193354/http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/arts_et_spectacles/2014/05/26/006-palmares-cannes-couts-budget-films-mommy-xavier-dolan.shtml|archive-date=19 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| gross          = $13.1 million<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=mommy.htm |title=Mommy (2014) |last= |first= |date= |accessdate=17 August 2016 |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305160943/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=mommy.htm |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Mommy''''' is a 2014 Canadian [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Xavier Dolan]] and starring [[Anne Dorval]], [[Antoine Olivier Pilon]], and [[Suzanne Cl\u00e9ment]]. The story concerns a mother with a sometimes-violent teenage son, struggling to control his behaviour in a hypothetical future in which parents have the legal option to commit troubled youth to public hospitals.\n\nThe story focuses on mother\u2013son relationships, a reoccurring theme in Dolan's work, and also marks his fourth collaboration with Dorval and his third with Cl\u00e9ment. Inspiration for this particular story was drawn from Dolan's discovery of Pilon and the music of [[Ludovico Einaudi]]. It was shot in Quebec in an unconventional 1:1 [[aspect ratio (image)|aspect ratio]].\n\nThe film debuted at the [[2014 Cannes Film Festival]], where it won the [[Jury Prize (Cannes Film Festival)|Jury Prize]]. It subsequently became a critical and financial success, grossing over [[United States dollar|$]]13 million worldwide. ''Mommy'' went on to win numerous other awards, among them nine [[3rd Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Awards]], including [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Motion Picture]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn a fictional outcome for the [[2015 Canadian federal election]], a political party comes to power and establishes a law called S-14, allowing parents of troubled children and limited finances to place their children in hospitals, without regard for [[fundamental justice]].\n\nAfter the law is passed, Diane \"Die\" Despr\u00e9s, a widowed mother and 46-year-old journalist, picks up her son Steve, who has [[ADHD]] with violent tendencies, from an institution. Steve has started a fire at the institution, in which another youth was injured. Die brings Steve to their new home in [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]] and struggles to care for him under financial distress. He gives her a cart full of groceries and a necklace reading \"Mommy\", which she suspects that he has stolen. Enraged by the accusation, Steve begins choking her, and she defends herself by hitting him with a glass frame. Whilst chaos ensues  Kyla, a neighbour and teacher on sabbatical, shows up to tend to their wounds.\n\nKyla, who is dealing with a [[stutter]]ing problem, begins to tutor Steve. After a disastrous tutoring session where Steve berates Kyla she snaps. After the confrontation Steve mellows and indicates he is glad to know her and respects her wishes not to call her \"babe\". Although the three have bonded, Die is served papers by the parents of the injured boy indicating she and Steve are being sued for the injuries caused by his fire.\n\nDie finds a lawyer willing to help them and the three of them go out for the evening for something to eat. They end up at a [[karaoke]] bar, where Steve is increasingly agitated by the atmosphere and what he sees as his mother, Die's sexual interest in the lawyer. Steve decides to sing, but is taunted by the audience, leading to a fight. Steve, Die and their lawyer argue, ending with Die slapping the lawyer for slapping Steve, which drives the lawyer away.\n\nDie continues to try and help her son and rebuild their lives, but while out shopping, with Steve and Kyla, Steve disappears and slits his wrist. He survives and a little later Die finds herself reflecting on all the dreams she had for her son to live a fulfilled happy life. She finally drives to a hospital to commit him under S-14; Steve angrily resists, and she regrets the decision when she sees the officials use violence and [[taser]]s to subdue him, but there is nothing she can legally do.\n\nKyla announces she is moving to [[Toronto]] and Die encourages her and expresses hope for Steve, but after Kyla leaves her alone in the house Die is shown to be extremely distressed at how things are resurfacing. Back at the hospital, Steve is being unstrapped from the straight-jacket by officials. Immediately after the straps are removed, Steve flees towards a large window.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Anne Dorval]] as Diane \"Die\" Despr\u00e9s\n* [[Antoine Olivier Pilon]] as Steve Despr\u00e9s\n* [[Suzanne Cl\u00e9ment]] as Kyla\n* Alexandre Goyette as Patrick\n* [[Patrick Huard]] as Paul B\u00e9liveau\n* Steven Chevrin as older Steve<ref>{{cite tweet |user=xdolan |number=517232867005722624 |date=1 October 2014 |title=non. Steven Chevrin. Un tr\u00e8s beau mannequin alors je suis flatt\u00e9 merci! }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:Xavier Dolan Cannes 2014 2.jpg|thumb|Dolan wrote the screenplay and chose an unconventional aspect ratio for the film.]]\nDirector [[Xavier Dolan]] wrote the screenplay, though he said at the time he had never known a person with [[attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]] or the same behavioural disorders that the character Steve exhibits.<ref name=\"Seymour\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/10/xavier-dolan-mommy |title=Xavier Dolan: \u2018I just want to express myself \u2013 like Madonna\u2019 |last=Seymour |first=Tom |date=10 March 2015 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816194748/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/10/xavier-dolan-mommy |archive-date=16 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Dolan said his own mother is an inspiration for his writing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/xavier-dolans-mommy-dominates-film-categories-at-canadian-screen-awards/article23240713/ |title=Xavier Dolan\u2019s Mommy wins best picture at Canadian Screen Awards |last=Szklarski |first=Cassandra |date=1 March 2015 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915175533/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/xavier-dolans-mommy-dominates-film-categories-at-canadian-screen-awards/article23240713/ |archive-date=15 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWith Dolan acknowledging mother-son relationships have always been an underlying theme in his work, the specific idea for ''Mommy'' came about after directing [[Antoine Olivier Pilon]] in the music video for \"College Boy\" by [[Indochine (band)|Indochine]], finding him to be a great actor.<ref name=\"Slotek\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/10/01/xavier-dolan-revelling-in-mommys-success |title=Xavier Dolan revelling in 'Mommy's' success |last=Slotek |first=Jim |date=1 October 2014 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[Toronto Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919124055/http://www.torontosun.com/2014/10/01/xavier-dolan-revelling-in-mommys-success |archive-date=19 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Inspired by another song, \"Experience\" by [[Ludovico Einaudi]], he wrote a scene about a mother fantasizing about a future with her son that will never come to be, and wrote a story around it. Dolan stated it was important to show how unpredictable [[mental illness]] can be in a home.<ref name=\"Slotek\"/> The concept of the S-14 law was inspired by an article he had read about a mother who used a law to transfer custody of a child to the state, although in an interview with ''[[Le Devoir]]'', Dolan could not recall which country this happened in.<ref name=\"Levesque\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ledevoir.com/culture/cinema/418292/la-belle-famille-de-mommy |title=La belle famille de Mommy |last=L\u00e9vesque |first=Fran\u00e7ois |date=13 September 2014 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[Le Devoir]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827103854/http://www.ledevoir.com/culture/cinema/418292/la-belle-famille-de-mommy |archive-date=27 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n''Mommy'' was filmed in [[Longueuil, Quebec]].<ref name=\"JeanetteKelly\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/xavier-dolan-brings-mommy-back-home-to-montreal-1.2760567 |title=Xavier Dolan brings Mommy back home to Montreal |last=Kelly |first=Jeanette |date=9 September 2014 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119144509/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/xavier-dolan-brings-mommy-back-home-to-montreal-1.2760567 |archive-date=19 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Dolan said that when filming, the actors and crew were often rewriting their lines.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2015/01/xavier-dolan-gets-real-reveals-mommy-oscar-jitters-tom-at-the-farm-whereabouts-and-more-189242/ |title=Xavier Dolan Gets Real, Reveals \u2018Mommy\u2019 Oscar Jitters, \u2018Tom at the Farm\u2019 Whereabouts and More |last=Lattanzio |first=Ryan |date=19 January 2015 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[IndieWire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822115933/http://www.indiewire.com/2015/01/xavier-dolan-gets-real-reveals-mommy-oscar-jitters-tom-at-the-farm-whereabouts-and-more-189242/ |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In casting actresses [[Anne Dorval]] and [[Suzanne Cl\u00e9ment]], whom Dolan had worked with before, he assigned them roles that he felt were the opposite of what each had previously played.<ref name=\"Levesque\"/>\n\nThe film was shot with a handheld camera,<ref name=\"Seymour\"/> in a 1:1 [[aspect ratio (image)|aspect ratio]], although most modern films are shot in 1.85:1 or 2.35:1 aspect ratios. On the unusual aspect ratio, Xavier Dolan said, \"I know a lot of people are saying, 'Oh, 1:1, how pretentious.' But for me, it seems a more humble and private format, a little more fitting to these lives we're diving into. Cinemascope [2.35:1] would have been extremely pretentious and incompatible for ''Mommy''. To try to get in that apartment and film these people in that aspect ratio would have been unseemly.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=O'Falt, Chris|title=Why Xavier Dolan's 'Mommy' Was Shot as a Perfect Square|date=8 January 2015|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/why-xavier-dolans-mommy-was-756857|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=1 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412123221/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/why-xavier-dolans-mommy-was-756857|archive-date=12 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He also said cinematographer [[Andr\u00e9 Turpin]] had long wanted to experiment with the format.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ledevoir.com/culture/cinema/409024/67e-festival-de-cannes-le-cas-mommy |title=Le cas Mommy |last=Tremblay |first=Odile |date=23 May 2014 |accessdate=17 August 2016 |work=[[Le Devoir]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827134634/http://www.ledevoir.com/culture/cinema/409024/67e-festival-de-cannes-le-cas-mommy |archive-date=27 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Dolan denied the ratio was meant to invoke the website [[Instagram]], emphasizing this is the original aspect ratio in film history.<ref name=\"Olsen\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-ca-xavier-dolan-20150118-story.html |title=In 'Mommy,' Xavier Dolan looks things in the eye |last=Olsen |first=Mark |date=17 January 2015 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827185234/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-ca-xavier-dolan-20150118-story.html |archive-date=27 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered on 22 May 2014, at the Cannes Film Festival, concluding with a 13-minute standing ovation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/2014/05/23/lovation-de-xavier-dolan-vous-donnera-des-frissons-video_n_5379301.html | title=Festival de Cannes: Xavier Dolan a eu droit \u00e0 une ovation qui vous donnera des frissons | date=25 May 2014 | work=Le Huffington Post | language=French | accessdate=13 October 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006174019/http://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/2014/05/23/lovation-de-xavier-dolan-vous-donnera-des-frissons-video_n_5379301.html | archive-date=6 October 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The film opened in [[Montreal]] on 8 September,<ref name=\"JeanetteKelly\"/> and in [[Toronto]] on 3 October.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/xavier-dolan-s-mommy-tapped-for-possible-oscar-contention-1.2771953 |title=Xavier Dolan\u2019s Mommy tapped for possible Oscar contention |last=The Canadian Press |first= |date=19 September 2014 |accessdate=19 March 2017 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118190330/http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/xavier-dolan-s-mommy-tapped-for-possible-oscar-contention-1.2771953 |archive-date=18 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In France, the film was distributed by Diaphana Films, with associate company [[agn\u00e8s b.]] selling Mommy necklaces to promote the film.<ref name=\"Ernst\">{{Cite web |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2014/12/09/director-of-the-year-french-language-film-xavier-dolan/ |title=Director of the Year, French-language film: Xavier Dolan |last=Ernst |first=Thom |date=9 December 2014 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821174134/http://playbackonline.ca/2014/12/09/director-of-the-year-french-language-film-xavier-dolan/ |archive-date=21 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film's U.S. distributor [[Roadside Attractions]] waited until 2015 for its release.<ref name=\"Ernst\"/>\n\nThe film became available on the U.K. [[Netflix]] in 2016, with Dolan publicly criticizing the company for altering the unconventional aspect ratio and demanding, \"Take it as it is, or remove it.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/xavier-dolan-mommy-netflix-1.3388973 |title=Xavier Dolan blasts Netflix for altering aspect ratio of drama Mommy |last=Wong |first=Jessica |date=4 January 2016 |accessdate=19 March 2017 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301154346/http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/xavier-dolan-mommy-netflix-1.3388973 |archive-date=1 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Netflix corrected the ratio hours later.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/05/xavier-dolan-victory-netflix-uk-mommy-aspect-ratio |title=Xavier Dolan triumphs in row with Netflix UK over his film's aspect ratio |last=Child |first=Ben |date=5 January 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918135704/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/05/xavier-dolan-victory-netflix-uk-mommy-aspect-ratio |archive-date=18 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nOn its opening weekend in Quebec, the film grossed $471,902.<ref name=\"Ernst\"/> ''Mommy'' was Dolan's first film to achieve success at the box office, grossing over $3.5&nbsp;million domestically in 2014, becoming the highest-selling film in Quebec for 2014.<ref name=kelly>{{cite news|title = Mommy continues its box office dominance|url = https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/arts/mommy-continues-its-box-office-dominance|work = Montreal Gazette|first = Brendan|last = Kelly|date = 18 November 2014|accessdate = 30 November 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151208165525/http://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/arts/mommy-continues-its-box-office-dominance|archive-date = 8 December 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> In Canada alone, it reached the $2 million gross on 16 October.<ref name=\"Ernst\"/>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Montreal Gazette]]'', over one million people went to see the film in France.<ref name=kelly /> The film ended its run on 19 March 2015 after making $3.5 million in North America and $9.6 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $13.1 million.<ref name=\"Mojo\"/>\n\n===Critical reception===\n[[File:Anne_Dorval_Cannes_2015.jpg|thumb|[[Anne Dorval]] received positive reviews for her performance and won the [[3rd Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] for [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress]].]]\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film received an approval rating of 89%, with an average score of 7.88/10 based on 127 reviews; the site's consensus states: \"As challenging as it is rewarding, ''Mommy'' finds writer-director Xavier Dolan taking another impressive step forward\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mommy_2015/|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|title=Mommy|date=17 August 2016|accessdate=17 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011054647/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mommy_2015/|archive-date=11 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds an average score of 74, based on 34 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\" in accordance with the website's standards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mommy|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/mommy|website=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive Inc|accessdate=21 January 2015|date=21 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123044847/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/mommy|archive-date=23 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, David Berry of the ''[[National Post]]'' gave the film four stars, writing, \"As a movie, ''Mommy'' is a very similar thing to its namesake jewellery, a flashy, scary, gorgeous little piece of home, a shiny bauble that still manages to hang very close to the heart\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/movies/mommy-reviewed-canadian-wunderkind-xavier-dolan-hits-it-out-of-the-park-with-oscar-vying-fifth-film |title=Mommy, reviewed: Canadian wunderkind Xavier Dolan hits it out of the park with Oscar-vying fifth film |last=Berry |first=David |date=3 October 2014 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[National Post]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712005643/http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/movies/mommy-reviewed-canadian-wunderkind-xavier-dolan-hits-it-out-of-the-park-with-oscar-vying-fifth-film |archive-date=12 July 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brendan Kelly of the ''[[Montreal Gazette]]'' gave it five out of five stars, calling it \"the absurdly prolific young auteur\u2019s best film yet\" and \"an ode to the strength of tough working-class single mothers everywhere\", and praising [[Anne Dorval]] as \"extraordinary\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/movie-guide/Review+Mommy+Xavier+Dolan+dearest+movie/10214722/story.html |title=Review: Mommy is Xavier Dolan\u2019s dearest movie yet |last=Kelly |first=Brendan |date=19 September 2014 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[Montreal Gazette]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160824080708/http://www.montrealgazette.com/entertainment/movie-guide/review+mommy+xavier+dolan+dearest+movie/10214722/story.html |archive-date=24 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Brian D. Johnson]] of ''[[Maclean's]]'' credited Dorval for an award-worthy \"powerhouse performance\". Johnson saw ''Mommy'' as more mature than Dolan's previous ''[[I Killed My Mother]]'', writing \"the tables are turned\" in writing the film from the mother's perspective.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.macleans.ca/authors/brian-d-johnson/xavier-dolans-mommy-electrifies-cannes/ |title=Blown away by Xavier Dolan\u2019s \u2018Mommy\u2019 |last=Johnson |first=Brian D. |date=2 March 2015 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[Maclean's]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524112851/http://www.macleans.ca/authors/brian-d-johnson/xavier-dolans-mommy-electrifies-cannes/ |archive-date=24 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Peter Howell of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' gave the film four stars, saying its [[smartphone]]-style picture made it timely and concluding it was \"one of the best movies of the year, period\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2014/10/02/mommy_burns_beyond_the_frame_review.html |title=Mommy burns beyond the frame: review |last=Howell |first=Peter |date=2 October 2014 |accessdate=17 August 2016 |work=[[Toronto Star]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822122757/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2014/10/02/mommy_burns_beyond_the_frame_review.html |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Liam Lacey at ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' gave the film three stars, calling the introductory information about S-14 \"clumsy\", but added \"What makes the flaws forgivable is Dolan's love of his characters\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/mommy-a-shared-history-of-love-hope-and-profanity/article20894596/ |title=Mommy: A shared history of love, hope and profanity |last=Lacey |first=Liam |date=3 October 2014 |accessdate=17 August 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915214128/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/mommy-a-shared-history-of-love-hope-and-profanity/article20894596/ |archive-date=15 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2014, ''Mommy'' received a four-star rating from ''[[The Guardian]]'' reviewer [[Peter Bradshaw]], who described the film as \"a splashy, transgressive treat, from trailer-trash chat to unexpected sex and surprising emotional depth\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=[[Peter Bradshaw]]|title=Cannes 2014 review: Mommy - dearest work yet from Xavier Dolan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/may/21/cannes-2014-review-mommy|accessdate=1 June 2014|work=The Guardian|agency=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=21 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140601221933/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/may/21/cannes-2014-review-mommy|archive-date=1 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>  Following Dolan's receipt of the Jury Prize at the 2014 Cannes Film Festival, ''Guardian'' writer Xan Brooks introduced the film as \"a boisterous Oedipal comedy\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=Xan Brooks|title=Cannes festival ready for shut-eye after Winter Sleep wins Palme d'Or|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/may/25/cannes-2014-winter-sleep-palme-d-or-timothy-spall?CMP=EMCNEWEML6619I2|accessdate=1 June 2014|work=The Guardian|agency=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602200641/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/may/25/cannes-2014-winter-sleep-palme-d-or-timothy-spall?CMP=EMCNEWEML6619I2|archive-date=2 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Peter Debruge of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"A funny, heartbreaking and, above all, original work\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/festivals/cannes-film-review-xavier-dolans-mommy-1201188655/ |title=Film Review: \u2018Mommy\u2019 |last=Debruge |first=Peter |date=21 May 2014 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809175707/http://variety.com/2014/film/festivals/cannes-film-review-xavier-dolans-mommy-1201188655/ |archive-date=9 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mark Olsen of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote the film \"feels like nothing less than Dolan's magnum opus, for the time being at least\".<ref name=\"Olsen\"/> Sandra Hall of the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'' wrote that while she initially found there was \"too much noise, too many emotional eruptions and too many tone-deaf subtitles\", she found Pilon and Dorval's performances to be \"remarkable\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/mommy-review-newlook-anne-dorval-shines-in-xavier-dolans-homage-to-motherhood-20150330-1mb02z.html |title=Mommy review: New-look Anne Dorval shines in Xavier Dolan's homage to motherhood |last=Hall |first=Sandra |date=5 April 2015 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011130535/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/mommy-review-newlook-anne-dorval-shines-in-xavier-dolans-homage-to-motherhood-20150330-1mb02z.html |archive-date=11 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the film three and a half stars, calling it rattling.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/mommy-20150121 |title=Mommy |last=Travers |first=Peter |date=21 January 2015 |accessdate=17 August 2016 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826233132/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/mommy-20150121 |archive-date=26 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''{{'}}s Joe Morgenstern, while finding the acting \"powerful\", found fault in the aspect ratio.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mommy-review-a-complex-relationship-1421955892 |title=\u2018Mommy\u2019 Review: A Complex Relationship |last=Morgenstern |first=Joe |date=22 January 2015 |accessdate=17 August 2016 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429063812/http://www.wsj.com/articles/mommy-review-a-complex-relationship-1421955892 |archive-date=29 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>  [[Richard Brody]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' panned the film, saying the depiction of Steve \"has no basis in psychology; rather, it appears as Dolan's own pseudo-transgressive artistic tantrum\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newyorker.com/goings-on-about-town/movies/mommy |title=Mommy |last=Brody |first=Richard |date= |accessdate=17 August 2016 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725171714/http://www.newyorker.com/goings-on-about-town/movies/mommy |archive-date=25 July 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe film was selected to compete for the [[Palme d'Or]] in the main competition section at the [[2014 Cannes Film Festival]],<ref name=\"Cannes2014\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/60533.html |title=2014 Official Selection |accessdate=17 April 2014 |work=Cannes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419012319/http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/60533.html |archive-date=19 April 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> where it won the [[Jury Prize (Cannes Film Festival)|Jury Prize]].<ref name=\"2014Winners\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/awardCompetition.html |title=Awards 2014 : Competition |accessdate=25 May 2014 |work=Cannes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527200255/http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/awardCompetition.html |archivedate=27 May 2014}}</ref> The film also won nine awards at the [[3rd Canadian Screen Awards]] in 2015, including [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Motion Picture]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/canadian-screen-awards-2015-mommy-big-film-winner-orphan-black-takes-top-tv-trophies-1.2977396 |title=Canadian Screen Awards 2015: Mommy big film winner, Orphan Black takes top TV trophies |last= |first= |date=1 March 2015 |accessdate= |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319211209/http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/canadian-screen-awards-2015-mommy-big-film-winner-orphan-black-takes-top-tv-trophies-1.2977396 |archive-date=19 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> and 10 awards at the [[17th Jutra Awards]], including Best Film. It was also [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Foreign Film|Best Foreign Film]] at the [[40th C\u00e9sar Awards]].\n\n''Mommy'' was selected as the Canadian entry for [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the 87th Academy Awards, but was not nominated.<ref name=\"Brampton\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bramptonguardian.com/whatson-story/4869864-dolan-s-mommy-canada-s-oscar-bid/ |title=Dolan's 'Mommy' Canada's Oscar bid |accessdate=19 September 2014 |work=Brampton Guardian |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010073357/http://www.bramptonguardian.com/whatson-story/4869864-dolan-s-mommy-canada-s-oscar-bid/ |archive-date=10 October 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name= \"HWROscar\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-canada-picks-mommy-foreign-734318 |title=Oscars: Canada Picks 'Mommy' For Foreign-Language Category |accessdate=19 September 2014 |work=Hollywood Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922015210/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-canada-picks-mommy-foreign-734318 |archive-date=22 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film was included in the list of \"Canada's Top Ten\" feature films of 2014, selected by a panel of filmmakers and industry professionals organized by TIFF.<ref>{{cite press release |title=TIFF Tips Its Toque to the Best in Canadian Filmmaking: Cronenberg, Dolan, and Gunnarson Among Directors Recognized |date=1 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://d12gbu3zt5gvms.cloudfront.net/docs/Lg5Q3v_14th_Annual_Canada%27s_Top_Ten_Film_Festival_2014___8510266_1418745501.pdf |publisher=TIFF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221204542/http://d12gbu3zt5gvms.cloudfront.net/docs/Lg5Q3v_14th_Annual_Canada%27s_Top_Ten_Film_Festival_2014___8510266_1418745501.pdf |archive-date=21 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Toronto Star |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2014/12/01/tiffs_top_ten_film_festival_spotlight_on_canadian_film.html |date=1 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |author=Linda Barnard |title=TIFF\u2019s Top Ten Film Festival: Spotlight on Canadian film |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221200903/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2014/12/01/tiffs_top_ten_film_festival_spotlight_on_canadian_film.html |archive-date=21 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\"|Award\n! scope=\"col\"|Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"|Category\n! scope=\"col\"|Recipient(s) \n! scope=\"col\"|Result\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref(s)|References}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |[[Camerimage]]\n|rowspan=1|2014\n| Bronze Frog \n| [[Andr\u00e9 Turpin]]\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=1|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/leviathan-wins-top-prize-at-camerimage-film-festival-for-cinematographers-1201362759/|title=\u2018Leviathan\u2019 Wins Top Prize at Camerimage, Film Festival for Cinematographers|accessdate=23 November 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141125032537/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/leviathan-wins-top-prize-at-camerimage-film-festival-for-cinematographers-1201362759/|archive-date=25 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=13|[[Canadian Screen Awards]]\n|rowspan=13|[[3rd Canadian Screen Awards|1 March 2015]]\n| [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Motion Picture]]\n| [[Xavier Dolan]] and [[Nancy Grant]]\n| {{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=13|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academy.ca/getmedia/04f8188b-08a6-4179-9f29-c6bbd083038a/2015_CSA_-Film_Nominations.aspx?ext=.pdfs|title=2015 Canadian Screen Awards Feature Film Nominations|date=13 January 2015|accessdate=13