lympic volleyball players of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players at the 2007 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players at the 2011 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in volleyball]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in volleyball]]\n[[Category:Opposite hitters]]\n[[Category:Outside hitters]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: 0-3 \u2192 0\u20133 (2), annouced \u2192 announced", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheilla_Castro"}
{"title_page": "28th century", "text_new": "{{ref improve|date=July 2017}}\n{{redirect|2707|the cancelled developed plane|Boeing 2707}}\n{{Centurybox|28}}\n\nThe '''28th century''' in the [[anno Domini]] or [[Common Era]] of the [[Gregorian calendar]] will begin on January 1, 2701 andyj8m6ju end on December 31, 2800. Unlike most century years, the year 2800 will be a [[leap year]], and the next [[century leap year]] after [[2400]].\n\n== Astronomical events ==\n\n===List of the long total solar eclipses===\n* July 21, 2707: [[Solar eclipse]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2707-07-21.gif|title= Solar eclipse of July 21, 2707|publisher=}}</ref> (5 min 48 s), of [[saros (astronomy)|saros]] 157.\n* July 31, 2725: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2725-07-31.gif|title= Solar eclipse of July 31, 2725|publisher=}}</ref> (5 min 57 s), of [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEsaros/SEsaros157.html  saros 157], \"crowning\" this series.\n* August 12, 2743: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2743-08-12.gif|title= Solar eclipse of August 12, 2743|publisher=}}</ref> (5 min 56 s), of saros 157.\n* July 31, 2744: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2744-07-31.gif|title= Solar eclipse of July 31, 2744|publisher=}}</ref> (5 min 59 s), of saros 167.<ref group=\"Note\">The saros 167 presents eclipses with very similar to those of the [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEsaros/SEsaros145.html  saros 145]. For example, the [http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2726-07-21.gif  Solar eclipse of July 21, 2726] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808011135/http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2726-07-21.gif |date=2007-08-08 }} (5 min 43 s), the previous one of the July 31, 2744 in this series of saros 167, would have a pathway very similar to the last one of the last millennium taken on [[Solar eclipse of August 11, 1999|August 11, 1999]], one of the series of saros 145. It would happen at a far anniversary of the first step on the Moon by [[Neil Armstrong]], in 1969. It would also be ''1 millennium, 2 years, 2 months, minus 1 day'' (calendar durations) after the historical [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/1701-1800/1724-05-22.gif  eclipse of May 22, 1724] (29th of saros 133), which was seen by [[Jacques Cassini]] and the king [[Louis XV]]. And obviously, this solar eclipse of July 31, 2744 in this series of saros 167, would have a pathway very similar to the one of the first \"US Solar Eclipse of the 21st century\" on [[Solar eclipse of August 21, 2017|August 21, 2017]], the following one of the series of saros 145.</ref>\n* August 12, 2762: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2762-08-12.gif|title= Solar eclipse of August 12, 2762|publisher=}}</ref> (6 min 11 s), of saros 167.\n* August 22, 2780: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2780-08-22.gif|title= Solar eclipse of August 22, 2780|publisher=}}</ref> (6 min 16 s), of [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEsaros/SEsaros167.html  saros 167], \"crowning\" this series.\n* September 2, 2798: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2798-09-02.gif|title= Solar eclipse of September 2, 2798|publisher=}}</ref> (6 min 14 s), of saros 167.\n\n===Other phenomena===\n* October 24, 2714: Transit of Jupiter from Uranus, the first one in 800 years (last time this occurred was on May 3, 1914).\n* September 8, 2729: The distance between Mars and [[the Earth]] will arrive at a new remarkable minimum, at 55,651,033.122&nbsp;km. <br />It will be the closer encounter of perihelic opposition slightly shorter (just 549&nbsp;km) than the previous one of the [[27th century#Other phenomena|September 3, 2650]].<ref>[meteorite-list] [http://www.mail-archive.com/meteorite-list@meteoritecentral.com/msg14044.html  Mars Makes Closest Approach In Nearly 60,000 Years], par Ron Baalke, on Friday August 22, 2003 at 09:04:54 -0700</ref>\n* June 15, 2733: [[Transit of Venus]].\n* June 13, 2741: Transit of Venus.\n* 2742: [[Triple conjunction]] [[Mars]]\u2013[[Jupiter]].\n* 2744: Triple conjunction Mars\u2013Jupiter.\n* 2761: Triple conjunction Mars\u2013[[Saturn]].\n* December 3, 2781: At 06:45 [[Universal Time|UTC]], Venus will [[occultation|occult]] [[Neptune]].\n* 2791: Triple conjunction Mars\u2013Jupiter.\n* 2794 / 2795: Triple conjunction Jupiter\u2013Saturn.\n\n== In fiction ==\n\n* The action of French [[Science fiction comics|science fiction comic book]] series ''[[Val\u00e9rian and Laureline]]'' begins in the 28th century. The first title, ''[[The City of Shifting Waters]]'' (''La cit\u00e9 des eaux mouvantes''), provides some information on the period of time itself, while the following title, ''[[Empire of a Thousand Planets]]'' (''L'empire des mille plan\u00e8tes''), mentions the precise date of September 23, 2720. The film ''[[Valerian and the City of a Thousand Planets]]'' is also mainly set in the 28th century.\n* The [[MMORPG]] ''[[Neocron]]'' is set in a [[post-apocalyptic]] 28th century.\n* The video game [[Destiny (video game)|Destiny]] is set in the 28th century, but the exact year is unknown.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20529785 \"Bungie's Destiny video game details leak online\" BBC News</ref>\n* ''[[Pitch Black (film)|Pitch Black]]'', ''[[The Chronicles of Riddick: Dark Fury]]'' and ''[[The Chronicles of Riddick]]'' are set in the 28th century.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}\n* The ''[[Doctor Who]]'' serial ''[[The Sensorites]]'' is set in an undetermined point in the 28th century.\n* In ''[[The Songs of Distant Earth]]'', a short story by Arthur C. Clarke, the [[ocean planet]] Thalassa is settled by human colonists around the year 2700.\n* The Time Traveler in the video game [[The Cave (video game)|The Cave]] is from the year 2701.\n* The video game ''Nancy Drew: Secret of the Scarlet Hand'' features an ending in which Nancy is entombed until she is discovered on October 23, 2702.\n* The video game ''[[Terminal Velocity (computer game)|Terminal Velocity]]'' is set in 2704.\n* The film [[Mutant Chronicles (film)|Mutant Chronicles]] is set is 2707.\n* The original video animation ''[[Coicent]]'' is set in 2710.\n* [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]]'s Metropolis concept album series ([[Metropolis: Suite I (The Chase)|I]], [[The ArchAndroid (Suites II and III)|II and III]]) is written from the perspective of an android from the year 2719.\n* The video game ''[[Ground Control II]]'' is set in 2741.\n* On the May 21, 2008 episode of the [[DirecTV]] soap opera [[Passions]], [[Tabitha Lenox]] tells [[Kay Bennett]] that an asteroid will hit the [[Earth]] in the year 2742.\n* The apocalyptic \"Seven Days of Fire\" in ''[[Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind (manga)|Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind]]'' apparently takes place within the 2750s, based on its description as occurring [[1000 (number)|1000]] years after the [[Industrial Revolution]].\n* The January 2762 sequence of the ''[[Babylon 5]]'' episode \"[[The Deconstruction of Falling Stars]]\" depicts the start of a [[nuclear war]] on Earth between the fascist Politdivision, which controlled the [[Earth Alliance (Babylon 5)|Earth Alliance]] government, and the Prole Sector. As a result of the conflict, which became known as the Great Burn, Earth regressed to a medieval level of technology. It was still in the process of rebuilding itself, with the clandestine assistance of the [[Ranger (Babylon 5)|Rangers]], [[4th millennium in fiction|500 years later]].\n* In the video game ''[[Starflight]]'', the Old Empire discovers the Thrynn and Elowan alien Races in 2770.\n* The [[Warner Brothers|WB]] show ''[[Loonatics Unleashed]]'' is set in 2772.\n* The Star League government in the ''[[Battletech]]'' timeline  collapses in 2784.\n* The video game ''[[Marathon (computer game)|Marathon]]'' is set in 2794.\n* ''[[Songs of a Dead Dreamer (album)|Songs of a Dead Dreamer]]'' references \"The Terran Invasion of [[Alpha Centauri]] Year 2794\".\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"Note\"/>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== Centuries and millennia ==\n{{Centuries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:28th Century}}\n[[Category:3rd millennium]]\n[[Category:Centuries]]\n[[Category:Centuries in the future]]\n[[Category:28th century| ]]\n[[Category:Future timelines|2800]]\n", "text_old": "{{ref improve|date=July 2017}}\n{{redirect|2707|the cancelled developed plane|Boeing 2707}}\n{{Centurybox|28}}\n\nThe '''28th century''' in the [[anno Domini]] or [[Common Era]] of the [[Gregorian calendar]] will begin on January 1, 2701 and end on December 31, 2800. Unlike most century years, the year 2800 will be a [[leap year]], and the next [[century leap year]] after [[2400]].\n\n== Astronomical events ==\n\n===List of the long total solar eclipses===\n* July 21, 2707: [[Solar eclipse]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2707-07-21.gif|title= Solar eclipse of July 21, 2707|publisher=}}</ref> (5 min 48 s), of [[saros (astronomy)|saros]] 157.\n* July 31, 2725: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2725-07-31.gif|title= Solar eclipse of July 31, 2725|publisher=}}</ref> (5 min 57 s), of [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEsaros/SEsaros157.html  saros 157], \"crowning\" this series.\n* August 12, 2743: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2743-08-12.gif|title= Solar eclipse of August 12, 2743|publisher=}}</ref> (5 min 56 s), of saros 157.\n* July 31, 2744: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2744-07-31.gif|title= Solar eclipse of July 31, 2744|publisher=}}</ref> (5 min 59 s), of saros 167.<ref group=\"Note\">The saros 167 presents eclipses with very similar to those of the [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEsaros/SEsaros145.html  saros 145]. For example, the [http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2726-07-21.gif  Solar eclipse of July 21, 2726] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808011135/http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2726-07-21.gif |date=2007-08-08 }} (5 min 43 s), the previous one of the July 31, 2744 in this series of saros 167, would have a pathway very similar to the last one of the last millennium taken on [[Solar eclipse of August 11, 1999|August 11, 1999]], one of the series of saros 145. It would happen at a far anniversary of the first step on the Moon by [[Neil Armstrong]], in 1969. It would also be ''1 millennium, 2 years, 2 months, minus 1 day'' (calendar durations) after the historical [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/1701-1800/1724-05-22.gif  eclipse of May 22, 1724] (29th of saros 133), which was seen by [[Jacques Cassini]] and the king [[Louis XV]]. And obviously, this solar eclipse of July 31, 2744 in this series of saros 167, would have a pathway very similar to the one of the first \"US Solar Eclipse of the 21st century\" on [[Solar eclipse of August 21, 2017|August 21, 2017]], the following one of the series of saros 145.</ref>\n* August 12, 2762: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2762-08-12.gif|title= Solar eclipse of August 12, 2762|publisher=}}</ref> (6 min 11 s), of saros 167.\n* August 22, 2780: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2780-08-22.gif|title= Solar eclipse of August 22, 2780|publisher=}}</ref> (6 min 16 s), of [http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEsaros/SEsaros167.html  saros 167], \"crowning\" this series.\n* September 2, 2798: Solar eclipse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCSEmap/2701-2800/2798-09-02.gif|title= Solar eclipse of September 2, 2798|publisher=}}</ref> (6 min 14 s), of saros 167.\n\n===Other phenomena===\n* October 24, 2714: Transit of Jupiter from Uranus, the first one in 800 years (last time this occurred was on May 3, 1914).\n* September 8, 2729: The distance between Mars and [[the Earth]] will arrive at a new remarkable minimum, at 55,651,033.122&nbsp;km. <br />It will be the closer encounter of perihelic opposition slightly shorter (just 549&nbsp;km) than the previous one of the [[27th century#Other phenomena|September 3, 2650]].<ref>[meteorite-list] [http://www.mail-archive.com/meteorite-list@meteoritecentral.com/msg14044.html  Mars Makes Closest Approach In Nearly 60,000 Years], par Ron Baalke, on Friday August 22, 2003 at 09:04:54 -0700</ref>\n* June 15, 2733: [[Transit of Venus]].\n* June 13, 2741: Transit of Venus.\n* 2742: [[Triple conjunction]] [[Mars]]\u2013[[Jupiter]].\n* 2744: Triple conjunction Mars\u2013Jupiter.\n* 2761: Triple conjunction Mars\u2013[[Saturn]].\n* December 3, 2781: At 06:45 [[Universal Time|UTC]], Venus will [[occultation|occult]] [[Neptune]].\n* 2791: Triple conjunction Mars\u2013Jupiter.\n* 2794 / 2795: Triple conjunction Jupiter\u2013Saturn.\n\n== In fiction ==\n\n* The action of French [[Science fiction comics|science fiction comic book]] series ''[[Val\u00e9rian and Laureline]]'' begins in the 28th century. The first title, ''[[The City of Shifting Waters]]'' (''La cit\u00e9 des eaux mouvantes''), provides some information on the period of time itself, while the following title, ''[[Empire of a Thousand Planets]]'' (''L'empire des mille plan\u00e8tes''), mentions the precise date of September 23, 2720. The film ''[[Valerian and the City of a Thousand Planets]]'' is also mainly set in the 28th century.\n* The [[MMORPG]] ''[[Neocron]]'' is set in a [[post-apocalyptic]] 28th century.\n* The video game [[Destiny (video game)|Destiny]] is set in the 28th century, but the exact year is unknown.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20529785 \"Bungie's Destiny video game details leak online\" BBC News</ref>\n* ''[[Pitch Black (film)|Pitch Black]]'', ''[[The Chronicles of Riddick: Dark Fury]]'' and ''[[The Chronicles of Riddick]]'' are set in the 28th century.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}\n* The ''[[Doctor Who]]'' serial ''[[The Sensorites]]'' is set in an undetermined point in the 28th century.\n* In ''[[The Songs of Distant Earth]]'', a short story by Arthur C. Clarke, the [[ocean planet]] Thalassa is settled by human colonists around the year 2700.\n* The Time Traveler in the video game [[The Cave (video game)|The Cave]] is from the year 2701.\n* The video game ''Nancy Drew: Secret of the Scarlet Hand'' features an ending in which Nancy is entombed until she is discovered on October 23, 2702.\n* The video game ''[[Terminal Velocity (computer game)|Terminal Velocity]]'' is set in 2704.\n* The film [[Mutant Chronicles (film)|Mutant Chronicles]] is set is 2707.\n* The original video animation ''[[Coicent]]'' is set in 2710.\n* [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]]'s Metropolis concept album series ([[Metropolis: Suite I (The Chase)|I]], [[The ArchAndroid (Suites II and III)|II and III]]) is written from the perspective of an android from the year 2719.\n* The video game ''[[Ground Control II]]'' is set in 2741.\n* On the May 21, 2008 episode of the [[DirecTV]] soap opera [[Passions]], [[Tabitha Lenox]] tells [[Kay Bennett]] that an asteroid will hit the [[Earth]] in the year 2742.\n* The apocalyptic \"Seven Days of Fire\" in ''[[Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind (manga)|Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind]]'' apparently takes place within the 2750s, based on its description as occurring [[1000 (number)|1000]] years after the [[Industrial Revolution]].\n* The January 2762 sequence of the ''[[Babylon 5]]'' episode \"[[The Deconstruction of Falling Stars]]\" depicts the start of a [[nuclear war]] on Earth between the fascist Politdivision, which controlled the [[Earth Alliance (Babylon 5)|Earth Alliance]] government, and the Prole Sector. As a result of the conflict, which became known as the Great Burn, Earth regressed to a medieval level of technology. It was still in the process of rebuilding itself, with the clandestine assistance of the [[Ranger (Babylon 5)|Rangers]], [[4th millennium in fiction|500 years later]].\n* In the video game ''[[Starflight]]'', the Old Empire discovers the Thrynn and Elowan alien Races in 2770.\n* The [[Warner Brothers|WB]] show ''[[Loonatics Unleashed]]'' is set in 2772.\n* The Star League government in the ''[[Battletech]]'' timeline  collapses in 2784.\n* The video game ''[[Marathon (computer game)|Marathon]]'' is set in 2794.\n* ''[[Songs of a Dead Dreamer (album)|Songs of a Dead Dreamer]]'' references \"The Terran Invasion of [[Alpha Centauri]] Year 2794\".\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"Note\"/>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== Centuries and millennia ==\n{{Centuries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:28th Century}}\n[[Category:3rd millennium]]\n[[Category:Centuries]]\n[[Category:Centuries in the future]]\n[[Category:28th century| ]]\n[[Category:Future timelines|2800]]\n", "name_user": "14.199.113.215", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/28th_century"}
{"title_page": "Fulk III, Count of Anjou", "text_new": "{{ infobox nobility\n| name = Fulk III, Count of Anjou\n| image = Sceau de Foulques Nerra.jpg\n| caption = Seal of Fulk III\n| noble family = [[House of Ingelger]]\n| father = [[Geoffrey I, Count of Anjou]]\n| mother = [[Adelaide of Vermandois]]\n| spouse = Elisabeth of Vend\u00f4me<br />Hildegarde of Sundgau\n| birth_date = c.970\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death date|1040|6|21|df=y}} (aged 69-70)\n| death_place = [[Metz]]\n}}\n\n'''Fulk III, the Black''' (970\u20131040; {{lang-fro|Foulque Nerra}}) was an early [[Counts and Dukes of Anjou|Count of Anjou]] celebrated as one of the first great builders of [[Castle|medieval castles]]. It is estimated Fulk constructed approximately 100 castles, along with abbeys throughout the [[Loire Valley]] in what is now France. He fought successive wars with neighbors in [[Brittany]], [[Blois]], [[Poitou]] and [[Aquitaine]] and made four pilgrimages to [[Jerusalem]] during the course of his life. He had two wives and three children.\n\nFulk was a natural horseman and fearsome warrior with a keen sense of military strategy that bested most of his opponents. He was allied with the goals and aims of the [[Capetians]] against the dissipated [[Carolingians]] of his era. With his county seat at Angers, Fulk\u2019s bitter enemy was [[Eudes II of Blois]], his neighbor 128&nbsp;km east along the Loire River, at Tours. The two men traded towns, followers and insults throughout their lives.\n\nFulk finished his first castle at [[Ch\u00e2teau de Langeais|Langeais]], 104&nbsp;km east of Angers, on the banks of the Loire.{{sfn|Kennedy|1995|p=12}} Like many of his constructions, it began as a wooden tower, and was eventually replaced with a stone structure, fortified with exterior walls, and equipped with a thick-walled tower called a ''donjon'' in French (source of the English dungeon, which however implies a cellar, rather than a tower). He built it in the territory of Eudes I, Count of Blois, and they fought a battle over it in 994. But Eudes I died of a sudden illness, and his son and successor, Eudes II, did not manage to evict him.\n\nFulk continued building more towers in a slow encirclement of Tours:  [[Montbazon]], Montr\u00e9sor, Mirebeau, [[Montrichard]], [[Ch\u00e2teau de Loches|Loches]], and even the tower of Montboyau, erected just across the Loire from Tours in 1016. He also fortified the castles at [[Ch\u00e2teau d'Angers|Angers]], [[Ch\u00e2teau d'Amboise|Amboise]], Chateau-Gontier, [[Ch\u00e2teau de Chinon|Chinon]], Mayenne and Semblan\u00e7ay, among many others. \u201cThe construction of castles for the purpose of extending a ruler\u2019s power was part of Fulk ''Nerra''\u2019s strategy,\u201d wrote Peter Fraser Purton, in ''A History of Medieval Siege, c. 450\u20131220''.\n\nFulk was a devout Christian, who built, enlarged or endowed several abbeys and monasteries, such as the Abbey of [[Beaulieu-les-Loches]], Saint-Florent-le-Vieil, Saint-Aubin, and a  convent, Notre Dame de la Charit\u00e9 at Ronceray in Angers. Although he never learned to write, he endowed a school with revenue to provide poor students with an education. Fulk also undertook four [[pilgrimages]] to Jerusalem.\n\n== Family ==\nHe was the son of [[Geoffrey I, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey I of Anjou]], also known as Geoffrey ''Grisegonelle'', and [[Adele of Meaux|Ad\u00e9laide of Vermandois]].{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=262}} He had an older sister: Hermengarde (b. 960), who married [[Conan I of Rennes|Conan of Brittany]] and a younger brother Geoffrey.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=262}} A half-brother, Maurice, was born in 980.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=14}}\n\nFulk married Elisabeth de Vend\u00f4me (~979\u2013999), daughter of Count Bouchard of Vendome,{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=16}} and they had a daughter:\n* Ad\u00e8le.,{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=262}} married Bodon, son of Landry, Count of Nevers. Their eldest son, Bouchard, inherited Vend\u00f4me.\nElisabeth\u2019s death was recounted in the ''Chronicles of Saint-Florent'': Elisabeth occupied the citadel at Anger with some supporters and while under siege from Fulk, she suffered a fall from a great height, and then was burnt at the stake for [[adultery]].{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=76}}\n\nFulk married Hildegarde de [[Sundgau]], whose family was from Lorraine, around December 1005.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=100}} They had two children:\n*[[Geoffrey II, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey II]], in 1006,{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=102-103}} who became known as Geoffrey Martel, succeeded Fulk as [[Counts and Dukes of Anjou|Count of Anjou]] in 1040.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=253}}\n*[[Ermengarde of Anjou, Duchess of Burgundy|Ermengarde-Blanche]], around 1018.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=262}}\n\n== Combat ==\nFulk Nerra\u2019s first victory was in June 992 at [[Battle of Conquereuil]], where he managed to defeat [[Conan I of Rennes|Conan I, Duke of Brittany]]. Conan\u2019s territorial ambitions had been quashed by Geoffroy Grisgonelle in 980, and seven years later, he planned an ambush on Angers while Fulk was at the crowning of [[Robert II of France|Robert the Pious]]. Fulk and his men foiled the ambush, killing Conan\u2019s son, Alain, in the process. In 992 Fulk laid siege to Conan\u2019s castle at Nantes, but he slipped away to Conquereuil. Conan was killed in the battle, and Fulk installed a governor/regent, as the succeeding count was a child.\n\nWhile Fulk  and Eudes II fought many skirmishes over territory and alliances, their biggest battle occurred in July 1016 at [[Battle of Pontlevoy]]. Eudes marched 10,000 men southward toward Fulk\u2019s tower at Montboyau; meanwhile, Fulk and his much smaller group attacked him from behind. Fulk\u2019s men were routed, retreated, and Eudes, thinking the battle won, went for a swim in the Cher River. Reinforcements led by Herbert Wake-Dog of Maine arrived to help Fulk, fought and routed Eudes' surprised men. Several thousand were reported killed.<ref>[Christian Thevenot, ''Foulque Nerra'', Editions Alan Sutton, St. Cyr-sur-Loire, 2009]</ref>\n\n== Pilgrimages ==\nFulk also undertook four [[pilgrimages]] to Jerusalem--first and second as a penitent seeking forgiveness for sins and third and fourth to protect pilgrims. In 1003, Fulk traveled to Jerusalem for his first pilgrimage. The journey was across the Alps at the Grand Bernard Pass in today\u2019s Switzerland, over land to Bari in the southern Italian peninsula (a stop in Rome was usually made), by ship to the Holy Land. The travel took as long as six months, through deeply dangerous territory.<ref>[Jonathan Sumption, ''The Age of Pilgrimage, The Medieval Journey to God'', Paulist Press, 2003]</ref>\n\nFulk made a second pilgrimage in 1008, obliged to do so by the king as punishment after Fulk ordered the [[murder]] of an enemy. For his third and fourth trips, Fulk had a moral obligation to protect pilgrims in the years following the desecration of Jerusalem by the [[Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah|\"Mad Caliph\" Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah]], and provided armed security against robbers, murderers and enslavers along the route. In 1035, the third pilgrimage with [[Robert I, Duke of Normandy]] and in 1038, he made his final pilgrimage. He died in [[Metz]] in 1040 on his return from that trip, and was buried in the chapel of his monastery at [[Beaulieu-l\u00e8s-Loches|Beaulieu]].\n\n[[Image:ChristianBauer Chateau de Loches dungeon.jpg|thumb|200px|Fulk ''Nerra'''s castle keep at [[Loches]].]]\n\n== Succession ==\nGeoffroy Martel was Count of Anjou from 1040 to 1060, but had no children from either of two marriages. The Anjou title went to his nephews, the two sons of his sister Ermengarde-Blanche (m. Geoffroy V of Ch\u00e2teau-Landon). [[Geoffrey III, Count of Anjou|Geoffroy III ''Le Barbu'' (the Bearded)]] was Count of Anjou from 1060 to 1098; [[Fulk IV, Count of Anjou|Fulk IV R\u00e9chin (the Mouth)]] was count from 1098 to 1109. Fulk IV's grandson, [[Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey Plantagenet]], married [[Empress Matilda|Matilda]], heir to the English throne, and began the [[Plantagenet|House of Plantagenet]] line of English kings.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |first=Bernard S. |last=Bachrach |authorlink=Bernard Bachrach |title=Fulk Nerra, the Neo-Roman Consul, 987\u20131040 |publisher=University of California Press |year=1993}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |first=Hugh |last=Kennedy |title=Crusader Castles |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1995}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Geoffrey I, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey Grisegonelle]] | title=[[Count of Anjou]] | years=987\u20131040 | after=[[Geoffrey II, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey Martel]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fulk 03 Anjou}}\n[[Category:970 births]]\n[[Category:1040 deaths]]\n[[Category:House of Ingelger]]\n[[Category:Counts of Anjou]]\n[[Category:10th-century French people]]\n", "text_old": "{{ infobox nobility\n| name = Fulk III, Count of Anjou\n| image = Sceau de Foulques Nerra.jpg\n| caption = Seal of Fulk III\n| noble family = [[House of Ingelger]]\n| father = [[Geoffrey I, Count of Anjou]]\n| mother = [[Adelaide of Vermandois]]\n| spouse = Elisabeth of Vend\u00f4me<br />Hildegarde of Sundgau\n| birth_date = c.970\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death date|1040|6|21|df=y}} (aged 69-70)\n| death_place = [[Metz]]\n}}\n\n'''Fulk III, the Black''' (970\u20131040; {{lang-fro|Foulque Nerra}}) was an early [[Counts and Dukes of Anjou|Count of Anjou]] celebrated as one of the first great builders of [[Castle|medieval castles]]. It is estimated Fulk constructed approximately 100 castles, along with abbeys throughout the [[Loire Valley]] in what is now France. He fought successive wars with neighbors in [[Brittany]], [[Blois]], [[Poitou]] and [[Aquitaine]] and made four pilgrimages to [[Jerusalem]] during the course of his life. He had two wives and three children.\n\nFulk was a natural horseman and fearsome warrior with a keen sense of military strategy that bested most of his opponents. He was allied with the goals and aims of the [[Capetians]] against the dissipated [[Carolingians]] of his era. With his county seat at Angers, Fulk\u2019s bitter enemy was [[Eudes II of Blois]], his neighbor 128&nbsp;km east along the Loire River, at Tours. The two men traded towns, followers and insults throughout their lives.\n\nFulk finished his first castle at [[Ch\u00e2teau de Langeais|Langeais]], 104&nbsp;km east of Angers, on the banks of the Loire.{{sfn|Kennedy|1995|p=12}} Like many of his constructions, it began as a wooden tower, and was eventually replaced with a stone structure, fortified with exterior walls, and equipped with a thick-walled tower called a ''donjon'' in French (source of the English dungeon, which however implies a cellar, rather than a tower). He built it in the territory of Eudes I, Count of Blois, and they fought a battle over it in 994. But Eudes I died of a sudden illness, and his son and successor, Eudes II, did not manage to evict him.\n\nFulk continued building more towers in a slow encirclement of Tours:  [[Montbazon]], Montr\u00e9sor, Mirebeau, [[Montrichard]], [[Ch\u00e2teau de Loches|Loches]], and even the tower of Montboyau, erected just across the Loire from Tours in 1016. He also fortified the castles at [[Ch\u00e2teau d'Angers|Angers]], [[Ch\u00e2teau d'Amboise|Amboise]], Chateau-Gontier, [[Ch\u00e2teau de Chinon|Chinon]], Mayenne and Semblan\u00e7ay, among many others. \u201cThe construction of castles for the purpose of extending a ruler\u2019s power was part of Fulk ''Nerra''\u2019s strategy,\u201d wrote Peter Fraser Purton, in ''A History of Medieval Siege, c. 450\u20131220''.\n\nFulk was a devout Christian, who built, enlarged or endowed several abbeys and monasteries, such as the Abbey of [[Beaulieu-les-Loches]], Saint-Florent-le-Vieil, Saint-Aubin, and a  convent, Notre Dame de la Charit\u00e9 at Ronceray in Angers. Although he never learned to write, he endowed a school with revenue to provide poor students with an education. Fulk also undertook four [[pilgrimages]] to Jerusalem.\n\n== Family ==\nHe was the son of [[Geoffrey I, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey I of Anjou]], also known as Geoffrey ''Grisegonelle'', and [[Adele of Meaux|Ad\u00e9laide of Vermandois]].{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=262}} He had an older sister: Hermengarde (b. 960), who married [[Conan I of Rennes|Conan of Brittany]] and a younger brother Geoffrey.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=262}} A half-brother, Maurice, was born in 980.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=14}}\n\nFulk married Elisabeth de Vend\u00f4me (~979\u2013999), daughter of Count Bouchard of Vendome,{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=16}} and they had a daughter:\n* Ad\u00e8le.,{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=262}} married Bodon, son of Landry, Count of Nevers. Their eldest son, Bouchard, inherited Vend\u00f4me.\nElisabeth\u2019s death was recounted in the ''Chronicles of Saint-Florent'': Elisabeth occupied the citadel at Anger with some supporters and while under siege from Fulk, she suffered a fall from a great height, and then was burnt at the stake for [[adultery]].{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=76}}\n\nFulk married Hildegarde de [[Sundgau]], whose family was from Lorraine, around December 1005.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=100}} They had two children:\n*[[Geoffrey II, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey II]], in 1006,{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=102-103}} who became known as Geoffroy Martel, succeeded Fulk as [[Counts and Dukes of Anjou|Count of Anjou]] in 1040.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=253}}\n*[[Ermengarde of Anjou, Duchess of Burgundy|Ermengarde-Blanche]], around 1018.{{sfn|Bachrach|1993|p=262}}\n\n== Combat ==\nFulk Nerra\u2019s first victory was in June 992 at [[Battle of Conquereuil]], where he managed to defeat [[Conan I of Rennes|Conan I, Duke of Brittany]]. Conan\u2019s territorial ambitions had been quashed by Geoffroy Grisgonelle in 980, and seven years later, he planned an ambush on Angers while Fulk was at the crowning of [[Robert II of France|Robert the Pious]]. Fulk and his men foiled the ambush, killing Conan\u2019s son, Alain, in the process. In 992 Fulk laid siege to Conan\u2019s castle at Nantes, but he slipped away to Conquereuil. Conan was killed in the battle, and Fulk installed a governor/regent, as the succeeding count was a child.\n\nWhile Fulk  and Eudes II fought many skirmishes over territory and alliances, their biggest battle occurred in July 1016 at [[Battle of Pontlevoy]]. Eudes marched 10,000 men southward toward Fulk\u2019s tower at Montboyau; meanwhile, Fulk and his much smaller group attacked him from behind. Fulk\u2019s men were routed, retreated, and Eudes, thinking the battle won, went for a swim in the Cher River. Reinforcements led by Herbert Wake-Dog of Maine arrived to help Fulk, fought and routed Eudes' surprised men. Several thousand were reported killed.<ref>[Christian Thevenot, ''Foulque Nerra'', Editions Alan Sutton, St. Cyr-sur-Loire, 2009]</ref>\n\n== Pilgrimages ==\nFulk also undertook four [[pilgrimages]] to Jerusalem--first and second as a penitent seeking forgiveness for sins and third and fourth to protect pilgrims. In 1003, Fulk traveled to Jerusalem for his first pilgrimage. The journey was across the Alps at the Grand Bernard Pass in today\u2019s Switzerland, over land to Bari in the southern Italian peninsula (a stop in Rome was usually made), by ship to the Holy Land. The travel took as long as six months, through deeply dangerous territory.<ref>[Jonathan Sumption, ''The Age of Pilgrimage, The Medieval Journey to God'', Paulist Press, 2003]</ref>\n\nFulk made a second pilgrimage in 1008, obliged to do so by the king as punishment after Fulk ordered the [[murder]] of an enemy. For his third and fourth trips, Fulk had a moral obligation to protect pilgrims in the years following the desecration of Jerusalem by the [[Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah|\"Mad Caliph\" Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah]], and provided armed security against robbers, murderers and enslavers along the route. In 1035, the third pilgrimage with [[Robert I, Duke of Normandy]] and in 1038, he made his final pilgrimage. He died in [[Metz]] in 1040 on his return from that trip, and was buried in the chapel of his monastery at [[Beaulieu-l\u00e8s-Loches|Beaulieu]].\n\n[[Image:ChristianBauer Chateau de Loches dungeon.jpg|thumb|200px|Fulk ''Nerra'''s castle keep at [[Loches]].]]\n\n== Succession ==\nGeoffroy Martel was Count of Anjou from 1040 to 1060, but had no children from either of two marriages. The Anjou title went to his nephews, the two sons of his sister Ermengarde-Blanche (m. Geoffroy V of Ch\u00e2teau-Landon). [[Geoffrey III, Count of Anjou|Geoffroy III ''Le Barbu'' (the Bearded)]] was Count of Anjou from 1060 to 1098; [[Fulk IV, Count of Anjou|Fulk IV R\u00e9chin (the Mouth)]] was count from 1098 to 1109. Fulk IV's grandson, [[Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey Plantagenet]], married [[Empress Matilda|Matilda]], heir to the English throne, and began the [[Plantagenet|House of Plantagenet]] line of English kings.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |first=Bernard S. |last=Bachrach |authorlink=Bernard Bachrach |title=Fulk Nerra, the Neo-Roman Consul, 987\u20131040 |publisher=University of California Press |year=1993}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |first=Hugh |last=Kennedy |title=Crusader Castles |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1995}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Geoffrey I, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey Grisegonelle]] | title=[[Count of Anjou]] | years=987\u20131040 | after=[[Geoffrey II, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey Martel]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fulk 03 Anjou}}\n[[Category:970 births]]\n[[Category:1040 deaths]]\n[[Category:House of Ingelger]]\n[[Category:Counts of Anjou]]\n[[Category:10th-century French people]]\n", "name_user": "Yeldarbnothsa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fulk_III,_Count_of_Anjou"}
{"title_page": "Beverley Mitchell", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Beverley Mitchell\n| image              = Beverley Mitchell, Seventh Heaven star DF-SD-02-04992 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Mitchell in 2001\n| birthname          = Beverley Ann Mitchell\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1981|1|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Arcadia, California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Loyola Marymount University]]\n| occupation         = Actress, singer\n| yearsactive        = 1984\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Michael Cameron|2008}}\n| children           = 2\n}}\n\n'''Beverley Ann Mitchell''' (born January 22, 1981) is an American actress and [[country music]] singer. She is best known for her role as [[List of 7th Heaven characters#Lucy Camden|Lucy Camden]] on the television series ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=September 2017}}\nMitchell was born in Arcadia, California, to Sharon Mitchell (n\u00e9e Weisz), an office manager, and David Mitchell, an [[auto racing]] promoter. Her parents have since divorced and remarried and she has a half-brother, Giuseppe Tomasino, from her father's second marriage.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\nAfter graduating from [[Chaminade College Preparatory School (California)|Chaminade College Preparatory School]] in 1999, she enrolled at [[Loyola Marymount University]] where she majored in film production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stantondaily.com/beverly-mitchell-then-now/?singlepage=1|title=Beverley Mitchell Then & Now! \u2013 Stanton Daily|website=stantondaily.com|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMitchell's first major film role was in ''[[The Crow: City of Angels]]'', playing teenaged drug addict Grace. During the filming of ''The Crow'', in 1996, she auditioned as a child actress for the role of Mary Camden in a new family drama, ''7th Heaven''. Producers initially turned her down as they did not think she was suitable to play Mary. However, when she read for the part of sister Lucy, she was instantly cast. ''7th Heaven'' was very popular, lasting for 11 seasons.\n\nIn 2000, she had a small part in ''[[The Amanda Show]]'' as a customer in ''Moody's Point''.\n\nIn 2003, Mitchell played [[Erica Enders-Stevens]] in the [[Disney Channel]] original movie ''[[Right on Track]]'', based on the early career of the 2014 [[NHRA Mello Yello Drag Racing Series]] [[Pro Stock]] champion and her sister [[Courtney Enders]], who was played by [[Brie Larson]].\n\nIn 2005, during a hiatus from filming ''7th Heaven'', Mitchell played Laura Hunter in the horror sequel ''[[Saw 2]]''.\n\nHer lifelong dream of becoming a [[country music]] singer came true when, in 2006, she recorded her debut album, ''Beverley Mitchell'' with record producer D. Scott Miller in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. She co-wrote eight of the songs featured on the album, including the hit single \"Angel\".\n\nIn 2007, Mitchell starred in the TV movie ''I Know What I Saw'', which aired on the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] network. She also planned to record a second album, and hopes to record her own version of the song \"[[When You Say Nothing At All]]\" on the album.\n\nIn 2010, Mitchell joined the cast of ''[[The Secret Life of the American Teenager]]'' at the start of the third season as school counselor Katelyn O\u2019Malley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/mitchell-secret-life-1020731/|title=Exclusive: 7th Heaven Star Joins Secret Life|work=TVGuide|first=Gina|last=DiNunno|date=July 20, 2010|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, she was cast in the [[Pop (American TV network)|Pop]] ''[[Hollywood Darlings]]'' with fellow 1990s child stars [[Jodie Sweetin]] and [[Christine Lakin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jodie-sweetin-christine-lakin-beverley-874735|title=Jodie Sweetin, Christine Lakin, Beverley Mitchell to Star in Pop Comedy (Exclusive)|first=Lesley|last=Goldberg|date=15 March 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> The series premiered April 12, 2017.\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1997, Mitchell's 15-year-old friend Angela was killed in a car accident. In the book ''Chicken Soup for the Preteen Soul'', Mitchell described how the death deeply affected her. The ''7th Heaven'' episode \"Nothing Endures But Change\" was based on her experience.<ref>{{cite book|title=Chicken Soup for the Preteen Soul|year=2001|publisher=Scholastic, Inc.|isbn=9781453278994|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gnJTTy7RFNcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Chicken+Soup+for+the+Preteen+Soul&hl=en&sa=X&ei=vbbCUM27IIfs8wSaw4GwBw&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Beverley%20Mitchell&f=false}}</ref> Her hit song \"Angel\" which is featured on her debut album was also written for her late friend.\n\nOn New Year's Eve 2005, during a trip to [[Colorado]], Mitchell became engaged to her long-time boyfriend, accountant Michael Cameron. They had originally planned to get married in 2007, but decided to put the wedding on hold due to the release of Mitchell's debut album. The wedding took place on October 1, 2008 in [[Ravello]], [[Italy]] on the [[Amalfi Coast]]. Former ''7th Heaven'' castmates [[Jessica Biel]] and [[Mackenzie Rosman]] served as bridesmaids.<ref name=\"wedding1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/beverley-mitchell-gets-19263/|title=Beverley Mitchell Gets Married|work=TVGuide|accessdate=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\"wedding2\">{{cite web|url= https://people.com/celebrity/beverley-mitchell-gets-married-in-italy/|title=Beverley Mitchell Gets Married in Italy|work=People|accessdate=2019-12-06|first=Ulrica|last=Wihlborg}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2013, the couple welcomed their first child, a daughter named Kenzie Lynne Cameron.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://people.com/parents/beverley-mitchell-welcomes-daughter-kenzie-lynne/|title=Beverley Mitchell Welcomes Daughter Kenzie Lynne|work=People|accessdate=2019-12-06}}</ref> On September 4, 2014, she announced they were expecting their second child.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/beverley-mitchell-is-pregnant-7th-heaven-star-expecting-second-child-201449|title=Beverley Mitchell Is Pregnant: 7th Heaven Star Expecting Second Child|date=4 September 2014|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=16 September 2014|author=Esther Lee}}</ref> On January 28, 2015, she gave birth to a boy named Hutton Michael Cameron.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/beverley-mitchell-gives-birth-to-second-child-welcomes-baby-boy-2015102|title=Beverley Mitchell Gives Birth to Second Child, Welcomes Baby Boy With Husband Michael Cameron |publisher=USWeekly}}</ref> On March 17, 2020, she announced on Instagram that they are expecting their third child.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/beverley-mitchell-pregnant-after-miscarriage-twins-rainbow-baby/|title=7th Heaven Star Beverley Mitchell Reveals She's Pregnant After Losing Twins: 'Rainbow Baby'|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1990\n|''[[Big Brother Jake]]''\n|Cassie\n|\n|-\n|''[[Children of the Bride]]''\n|rowspan=2|Jersey\n|rowspan=2|TV movie\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Baby of the Bride]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1992\n|''[[Quantum Leap]]''\n|Becky Pruitt\n|Episode: \"Killin' Time\"\n|-\n|''[[Sinatra (TV miniseries)|Sinatra]]''\n|Little [[Nancy Sinatra|Nancy]] at 7\u20139\n|Miniseries\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1993\n|''[[Mother of the Bride (1993 film)|Mother of the Bride]]''\n|Jersey\n|TV movie\n|-\n|''[[Phenom (TV series)|Phenom]]''\n|Clare\n|Episodes: \"There's No Place Like Home\", \"A Lou-Daughter Picnic\"\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Melrose Place]]''\n|Katie Conners\n|Episode: \"No Strings Attached\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1995\n|''[[White Dwarf (1995 film)|White Dwarf]]''\n|XuXu\n|TV movie\n|-\n|''[[Baywatch]]''\n|Melissa\n|Episode: \"Hot Stuff\"\n|-\n|1996\n|''{{sortname|The|Faculty|The Faculty (TV series)}}''\n|Leslie\n|Episode: \"Behavior Among Adults\"\n|-\n|1996\u20132007\n|''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''\n|[[List of 7th Heaven characters#Lucy Camden-Kinkirk|Lucy Camden-Kinkirk]]\n|Main role (242 episodes)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2000\n|''[[Hey Arnold!]]''\n|Summer (voice)\n|Episode: \"Summer Love\"\n|-\n|''Girl Band''\n|Suzanne\n|rowspan=3|TV movie\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Right on Track]]''\n|[[Erica Enders]]\n|-\n|2008\n|''Post Mortem''\n|Mackenzie Greer\n|-\n|2011\u20132013\n|''{{sortname|The|Secret Life of the American Teenager}}''\n|Kaitlin O'Malley\n|Regular role (26 episodes)\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2012\n|''[[Get Out Alive]]''\n|Lucy Foster\n|TV movie\n|-\n|''[[The Haunting Of]]''\n|Self\n|Episode: \"'The Haunting Of' Beverley Mitchell\"\n|-\n|2015\n|''A Gift Wrapped Christmas''\n|Stephanie\n|rowspan=2|TV movie\n|-\n|2016 \n|''Deadly Dance Mom''\n|Beth Hoyson\n|-\n|2017\u20132018\n||''{{sortname|Hollywood|Darlings}}''\n|Herself\n|Main role    (16 episodes)\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1994\n|''Killing Obsession''\n|Annie\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''{{sortname|The|Crow: City of Angels}}''\n|Grace\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Mean People Suck]]''\n|Kate's Sister\n|Short film\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Saw II]]''\n|[[Laura Hunter]]\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Extreme Movie]]''\n|Sue\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Snowmen (film)|Snowmen]]''\n|Mrs. Sherbrook\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''Pennhurst''\n|Sarah\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2014\n|''{{sortname|The|Dog Who Saved Easter|nolink=1}}''\n|Alice\n|\n|-\n|''Toxin''\n|Isabelle\n|\n|}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=January 2015}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart<br />positions\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! width=\"45\"| [[Top Country Albums|US Country]]\n! width=\"45\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US Heat]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Beverley Mitchell (album)|Beverley Mitchell]]''\n| \n* Release date: January 23, 2007\n* Label: Daywind Records\n| 30\n| 8\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! style=\"width:22em;\"| Single\n! Album\n|-\n| 2006\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Angel\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''Beverley Mitchell''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2007\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Heaven on Earth Down Here\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Walking\"\n|-\n| 2009\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Let's Dream Like We're Gonna Live Forever\"\n|}\n\n=== Music videos ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! style=\"width:22em;\"| Video\n|-\n| 2007\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Heaven on Earth Down Here\"\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n;[[Young Artist Awards]]\n*1997: Best Performance in a Drama Series \u2013 Young Actress (''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]'') \u2013 '''Won'''\n*1998: Best Performance in a TV Drama Series \u2013 Leading Young Actress (''7th Heaven'') \u2013 '''Won'''\n*1999: Best Performance in a TV Series \u2013 Young Ensemble (''7th Heaven'') \u2013 ''Nominated'' (with [[Barry Watson (actor)|Barry Watson]], [[David Gallagher]], [[Jessica Biel]] and [[Mackenzie Rosman]])\n*2000: Best Performance in a TV Drama Series \u2013 Leading Young Actress (''7th Heaven'') \u2013 '''Won'''\n\n;[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n*2005: [[Teen Choice Award for Choice TV Actress Drama|Choice TV Actress: Drama]] (''7th Heaven'') \u2013 ''Nominated''\n\n;YoungStar Awards\n*1998: Best Performance by a Young Actress in a Drama TV Series (''7th Heaven'') \u2013 ''Nominated''\n*2000: Best Young Ensemble Cast \u2013 Television (''7th Heaven'') \u2013 ''Nominated'' (with David Gallagher, Jessica Biel and Mackenzie Rosman)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|0005238}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, Beverley}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female country singers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Loyola Marymount University alumni]]\n[[Category:Singers from California]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Beverley Mitchell\n| image              = Beverley Mitchell, Seventh Heaven star DF-SD-02-04992 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Mitchell in 2001\n| birthname          = Beverley Ann Mitchell\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1981|1|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Arcadia, California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Loyola Marymount University]]\n| occupation         = Actress, singer\n| yearsactive        = 1984\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Michael Cameron|2008}}\n| children           = 2\n}}\n\n'''Beverley Ann Mitchell''' (born January 22, 1981) is an American actress and [[country music]] singer. She is best known for her role as [[List of 7th Heaven characters#Lucy Camden|Lucy Camden]] on the television series ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=September 2017}}\nMitchell was born in Arcadia, California, to Sharon Mitchell (n\u00e9e Weisz), an office manager, and David Mitchell, an [[auto racing]] promoter. Her parents have since divorced and remarried and she has a half-brother, Giuseppe Tomasino, from her father's second marriage.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\nAfter graduating from [[Chaminade College Preparatory School (California)|Chaminade College Preparatory School]] in 1999, she enrolled at [[Loyola Marymount University]] where she majored in film production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stantondaily.com/beverly-mitchell-then-now/?singlepage=1|title=Beverley Mitchell Then & Now! \u2013 Stanton Daily|website=stantondaily.com|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMitchell's first major film role was in ''[[The Crow: City of Angels]]'', playing teenaged drug addict Grace. During the filming of ''The Crow'', in 1996, she auditioned as a child actress for the role of Mary Camden in a new family drama, ''7th Heaven''. Producers initially turned her down as they did not think she was suitable to play Mary. However, when she read for the part of sister Lucy, she was instantly cast. ''7th Heaven'' was very popular, lasting for 11 seasons.\n\nIn 2000, she had a small part in ''[[The Amanda Show]]'' as a customer in ''Moody's Point''.\n\nIn 2003, Mitchell played [[Erica Enders-Stevens]] in the [[Disney Channel]] original movie ''[[Right on Track]]'', based on the early career of the 2014 [[NHRA Mello Yello Drag Racing Series]] [[Pro Stock]] champion and her sister [[Courtney Enders]], who was played by [[Brie Larson]].\n\nIn 2005, during a hiatus from filming ''7th Heaven'', Mitchell played Laura Hunter in the horror sequel ''[[Saw 2]]''.\n\nHer lifelong dream of becoming a [[country music]] singer came true when, in 2006, she recorded her debut album, ''Beverley Mitchell'' with record producer D. Scott Miller in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. She co-wrote eight of the songs featured on the album, including the hit single \"Angel\".\n\nIn 2007, Mitchell starred in the TV movie ''I Know What I Saw'', which aired on the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] network. She also planned to record a second album, and hopes to record her own version of the song \"[[When You Say Nothing At All]]\" on the album.\n\nIn 2010, Mitchell joined the cast of ''[[The Secret Life of the American Teenager]]'' at the start of the third season as school counselor Katelyn O\u2019Malley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/mitchell-secret-life-1020731/|title=Exclusive: 7th Heaven Star Joins Secret Life|work=TVGuide|first=Gina|last=DiNunno|date=July 20, 2010|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, she was cast in the [[Pop (American TV network)|Pop]] ''[[Hollywood Darlings]]'' with fellow 1990s child stars [[Jodie Sweetin]] and [[Christine Lakin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jodie-sweetin-christine-lakin-beverley-874735|title=Jodie Sweetin, Christine Lakin, Beverley Mitchell to Star in Pop Comedy (Exclusive)|first=Lesley|last=Goldberg|date=15 March 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> The series premiered April 12, 2017.\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1997, Mitchell's 15-year-old friend Angela was killed in a car accident. In the book ''Chicken Soup for the Preteen Soul'', Mitchell described how the death deeply affected her. The ''7th Heaven'' episode \"Nothing Endures But Change\" was based on her experience.<ref>{{cite book|title=Chicken Soup for the Preteen Soul|year=2001|publisher=Scholastic, Inc.|isbn=9781453278994|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gnJTTy7RFNcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Chicken+Soup+for+the+Preteen+Soul&hl=en&sa=X&ei=vbbCUM27IIfs8wSaw4GwBw&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Beverley%20Mitchell&f=false}}</ref> Her hit song \"Angel\" which is featured on her debut album was also written for her late friend.\n\nOn New Year's Eve 2005, during a trip to [[Colorado]], Mitchell became engaged to her long-time boyfriend, accountant Michael Cameron. They had originally planned to get married in 2007, but decided to put the wedding on hold due to the release of Mitchell's debut album. The wedding took place on October 1, 2008 in [[Ravello]], [[Italy]] on the [[Amalfi Coast]]. Former ''7th Heaven'' castmates [[Jessica Biel]] and [[Mackenzie Rosman]] served as bridesmaids.<ref name=\"wedding1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/beverley-mitchell-gets-19263/|title=Beverley Mitchell Gets Married|work=TVGuide|accessdate=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\"wedding2\">{{cite web|url= https://people.com/celebrity/beverley-mitchell-gets-married-in-italy/|title=Beverley Mitchell Gets Married in Italy|work=People|accessdate=2019-12-06|first=Ulrica|last=Wihlborg}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2013, the couple welcomed their first child, a daughter named Kenzie Lynne Cameron.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://people.com/parents/beverley-mitchell-welcomes-daughter-kenzie-lynne/|title=Beverley Mitchell Welcomes Daughter Kenzie Lynne|work=People|accessdate=2019-12-06}}</ref> On September 4, 2014, she announced they were expecting their second child.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/beverley-mitchell-is-pregnant-7th-heaven-star-expecting-second-child-201449|title=Beverley Mitchell Is Pregnant: 7th Heaven Star Expecting Second Child|date=4 September 2014|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=16 September 2014|author=Esther Lee}}</ref> On January 28, 2015, she gave birth to a boy named Hutton Michael Cameron.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/beverley-mitchell-gives-birth-to-second-child-welcomes-baby-boy-2015102|title=Beverley Mitchell Gives Birth to Second Child, Welcomes Baby Boy With Husband Michael Cameron |publisher=USWeekly}}</ref> On March 17, 2020, she annouced on Instagram that they are expecting their third child.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/beverley-mitchell-pregnant-after-miscarriage-twins-rainbow-baby/|title=7th Heaven Star Beverley Mitchell Reveals She's Pregnant After Losing Twins: 'Rainbow Baby'|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1990\n|''[[Big Brother Jake]]''\n|Cassie\n|\n|-\n|''[[Children of the Bride]]''\n|rowspan=2|Jersey\n|rowspan=2|TV 